title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 36 snub nose .38 Special revolver
postcontent: I have for sale a circa 1968 Smith & Wesson Model 36 (no dash) snub nose .38 Special steel revolver with a six digit serial number beginning with 666.Designed to be small and compact for easy carry conceal or small storage areas, this Model 36 has a pinned 1.875 inch (sometimes called a 2 inch) barrel. It has 5-round capacity in a swing-out cylinder and exposed hammer. This gun has a grooved rear sight and a ramped fixed blade front sight. It features a blued finish with wood grips. One grip is a darker shade than the other, something I didn't notice until I had them off and they were on the table side-by-side while I was cleaning the gun.This most intriguing aspect of this pistol is that it has areas with a black cherry color to them. This is most apparent under bright light, with the barrel and lug showing the most pronounced tone and the cylinder having a slightly black cherry tint.  There are many theories on why some of some blued guns take on that black cherry tint, because it also happens to brand-new never fired blued weapons. Some possibilities include the concentration of salts in the bluing process, alloy of the steel, parts of the gun being made in different batches at the S&W factory, subsequent rebluing, etc., but without knowing the entire chain of command and history of this gun is isn't possible to know the origin of the black cherry tinting on this pistol.This nearly fifty year old classic revolver is obviously used, but it is clean, nice for its age, and is a great little shooter at a good price. I have disclosed all I know about the gun in the interest of transparency, perhaps to the point of overstating the color issue. However, I want to ensure you have complete knowledge of all I know about this gun. I put fifty rounds of Winchester .38 Special manufactured ammo through it Thursday evening and it was accurate and fun to shoot. This will make a great carry conceal, recreational, range, shop, vehicle, or house gun.Please contact me for several additional pictures. Local face-to-face cash sale only. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions.

title: For Sale:  Marlin 1936
postcontent: Up for sale is a rare Marlin Model 1936. These guns preceded the 336, were made before micro-groove rifling (it has ballard rifling), and were only made a few years pre-war. They are collectible. Except this one.This gun has the receiver drilled and tapped. I am a collector, and that is a one-strike-and-out thing. Now, its virtues:Overall wear is good and honest! Bore is beautiful! Case hardening still visible on and under lever! This gun is chambered in the hard hitting "32 Special" (aka .32 Winchester Special). Lyman front sight with rear sight missing, but properly plugged with Williams blank.The receiver was professionally drilled; work performed by Bubba is nowhere to be found. Screw heads are nice all over. Nice, vintage Weaver see-through scope mounts and Tasco Pronghorn scope with good glass. Now, why one would put see-through mounts on a gun, then remove and plug the rear sight, eludes me.If the receiver had not been drilled and tapped, I'd be keeping this gun. It is that nice and honest. If you are looking for a level action deer rifle, this one would be hard to beat. Asking $349. Look at the quality of the current Marlin 336s, then see this gun. There will be no comparison.As a collector, let me know if you have an old gun you might want to trade. Worst I can say is, "no, thanks anyway". If it isn't more than 50 years old, I am not interested. Priority order of interest are lever actions then bolt actions, with Winchester leading the pack, or good number-matching military rifles.Thanks, and take care.
